# Requirements: Reseller Seeded Vocabularies

## Problem statement
The clothing Brand field already has a canonical-vocabulary system (`clothing_brands` table, `resolveCanonicalBrand` helper, `BrandCombobox.tsx`, shipped PR #12) that collapses casing variants ("Nike"/"nike"/"NIKE") into one record and offers a searchable "add new" combobox. The three other free-text clothing fields — color, material, and gender_department — still use plain text inputs backed only by a per-operator history datalist (`fetchFieldSuggestions`), so a new operator with no listing history gets no suggestions at all, and existing operators can still create silent duplicates ("Grey" vs "Gray", "Denim" vs "denim"). Separately, `clothing_brands` itself ships empty — even the one field that has the vocabulary machinery gives a first-time operator nothing to pick from until they've typed a brand once. This matters now because the app is meant to speed up listing clothing items with consistent, resale-marketplace-ready attribute values, and every empty or ad hoc vocabulary field works against that from item one.

## Users / stakeholders
- Reseller operators using the clothing intake form (`AddClothingForm.tsx`) to add inventory items.
- Multi-tenant households/businesses using this instance — each tenant's vocabulary is its own; no cross-tenant sharing.
- Future maintainers of the vocabulary/combobox pattern who will extend it to further fields.

## Functional requirements
1. The system shall create a new versioned SQL migration file (`012_...sql`, following the `NNN_description.sql` naming of files 001–011) that adds three new tables: `clothing_colors`, `clothing_materials`, and `clothing_departments`.
2. The system shall define each new table with columns `id` (TEXT PRIMARY KEY, UUID v4 format, matching the `CHECK (length(id) = 36 AND substr(id, 15, 1) = '4')` pattern used by `clothing_brands`), `tenant_id` (TEXT NOT NULL REFERENCES tenants(id)), `canonical_name` (TEXT NOT NULL, CHECK length(trim(canonical_name)) > 0), and `created_at` (TEXT NOT NULL DEFAULT datetime('now')), mirroring `clothing_brands` in `data/migrations/011_clothing_brand_and_size_system.sql`.
3. The system shall enforce `UNIQUE (tenant_id, canonical_name COLLATE NOCASE)` on each of `clothing_colors`, `clothing_materials`, and `clothing_departments`, so the same value cannot exist twice for one tenant differing only by case.
4. The system shall seed `clothing_colors` at migration time, for every existing tenant row, with exactly these 14 canonical values: Black, White, Gray, Navy, Red, Blue, Green, Yellow, Orange, Purple, Pink, Brown, Beige, Multicolor.
5. The system shall seed `clothing_materials` at migration time, for every existing tenant row, with exactly these 14 canonical values: Cotton, Polyester, Wool, Denim, Leather, Silk, Linen, Cashmere, Nylon, Spandex, Rayon, Fleece, Suede, Canvas.
6. The system shall seed `clothing_departments` at migration time, for every existing tenant row, with exactly these 5 canonical values: Men's, Women's, Kids', Unisex, Baby.
7. The system shall seed the existing `clothing_brands` table at migration time, for every existing tenant row, with these 25 canonical values: Nike, Adidas, Levi's, Zara, H&M, Gap, Old Navy, Ralph Lauren, Tommy Hilfiger, Calvin Klein, Coach, Michael Kors, Patagonia, The North Face, Lululemon, Under Armour, Vans, Converse, New Balance, Champion, Carhartt, J.Crew, Banana Republic, American Eagle, Free People.
8. The system shall seed the same starter vocabulary (brands, colors, materials, departments) for any tenant created after this migration runs, so no tenant — existing or future — starts with an empty vocabulary on any of these four fields.
9. The system shall not create duplicate rows if the migration is re-run against a database that already has seeded data (seed inserts must be idempotent, e.g. `INSERT OR IGNORE` or an existence check per tenant/value pair).
10. The system shall provide a `resolveCanonicalColor(tenantId, rawColor)` helper in `lib/colors.ts`, a `resolveCanonicalMaterial(tenantId, rawMaterial)` helper in `lib/materials.ts`, and a `resolveCanonicalDepartment(tenantId, rawDepartment)` helper in `lib/departments.ts`, each mirroring `resolveCanonicalBrand`'s contract in `lib/brands.ts`: trim input, case-insensitively look up an existing row for the tenant, return its stored `canonical_name` if found, otherwise insert a new row using the trimmed input and return it.
11. The system shall handle the concurrent-insert race in each new resolve-or-create helper the same way `resolveCanonicalBrand` does: on `SQLITE_CONSTRAINT_UNIQUE` from the INSERT, re-select the winning row's `canonical_name` and return it instead of throwing.
12. The system shall provide a corresponding `validateColorInput`, `validateMaterialInput`, and `validateDepartmentInput` function in each new lib file, mirroring `validateBrandInput`'s contract (string type, non-empty after trim, ≤255 characters) — since color and material are optional fields, empty/undefined input must be treated as "not provided" (valid, no resolve call) rather than invalid, matching current handling in `app/api/items/route.ts` lines 311–322.
13. The system shall wire `resolveCanonicalColor`, `resolveCanonicalMaterial`, and `resolveCanonicalDepartment` into the clothing item creation path in `app/api/items/route.ts`, calling each resolver only when its field is non-empty, so a submitted color/material/gender_department is persisted using its canonical casing rather than the raw typed casing.
14. The system shall add a `GET /api/colors`, `GET /api/materials`, and `GET /api/departments` endpoint, each mirroring `app/api/brands/route.ts`: authenticate via `requireTenant`, return that tenant's rows as `{ id, canonical_name }` ordered by `canonical_name COLLATE NOCASE`, capped at 200 rows, scoped to the caller's tenant only.
15. The system shall provide a reusable `VocabCombobox.tsx` component that generalizes `BrandCombobox.tsx`'s behavior (case-insensitive substring filtering of the canonical list, frequency-based reordering from `fetchFieldSuggestions`, "Add \"{typed}\" as a new {field label}" trailing option when no exact match exists, full ARIA combobox keyboard behavior — arrow up/down, Enter to select, Escape to close), parameterized at minimum by: the vocabulary API endpoint path, the `fetchFieldSuggestions` field key, the field label text, whether the field is required, and a max-length constant.
16. The system shall replace the plain `<input list="color-options">` / `<datalist>` in `AddClothingForm.tsx` (lines 249–261) with `VocabCombobox` configured for `/api/colors` and field key `color`.
17. The system shall replace the plain `<input list="material-options">` / `<datalist>` in `AddClothingForm.tsx` (lines 263–276) with `VocabCombobox` configured for `/api/materials` and field key `material`.
18. The system shall replace the plain `<input list="department-options">` / `<datalist>` in `AddClothingForm.tsx` (lines 278–292) with `VocabCombobox` configured for `/api/departments` and field key `gender_department`, preserving the existing "Department" label and non-required status.
19. The system shall preserve existing raw-typed-value commit-on-every-keystroke behavior in the new combobox for color/material/gender_department, so existing Playwright `.fill()`-based E2E helpers targeting these fields continue to work unchanged.
20. The system shall leave `brand`, `size_label`/`size_system` fields, `clothing_brands`/size-system tables, book-category fields (author, publisher), and `condition` (existing `ConditionSelect` CHECK-constraint enum) entirely untouched by this change.

## Non-functional requirements
- Each new `GET /api/{colors,materials,departments}` endpoint follows the same tenant-scoping and query-shape as `GET /api/brands` — no new performance characteristics; result sets are capped at 200 rows per the existing `LIMIT 200` pattern.
- Migration seed inserts must be re-run-safe (idempotent) so `npm run migrate` (or the project's migration runner) can execute more than once against the same database without erroring or duplicating rows.
- No new external dependencies — helpers, endpoints, and the combobox component use the same libraries already in use (`better-sqlite3`, `uuid`, existing React/Next.js patterns).
- Test coverage for new/changed code must meet the project's existing enforced thresholds (85/80/85/85 per README) — new lib helpers, API routes, and the `VocabCombobox` component each need unit/component/API test coverage comparable to their `clothing_brands` counterparts (`tests/api/brands.test.ts`, `components/__tests__/BrandCombobox.test.tsx`).

## Constraints
- Must integrate with the existing multi-tenant model: every new table scoped by `tenant_id`, every new endpoint gated by `requireTenant()`.
- Must follow the existing versioned-migration convention in `data/migrations/` (numbered, additive, no destructive schema changes to `clothing_details` or `items`).
- Must reuse the exact `id`/`UNIQUE(tenant_id, canonical_name COLLATE NOCASE)` schema shape already established by `clothing_brands` in migration 011 — no deviation in column set or constraint style across the three new tables.
- Must reuse `fetchFieldSuggestions` (`lib/suggestions.ts`) for the frequency-ranking signal in `VocabCombobox`, the same mechanism `BrandCombobox` already uses — do not introduce a second suggestions API.
- Never point migrations, tests, or seed scripts at `data/inventory.db` directly — all seeding must run through the project's scratch-database-by-default test/migration tooling (`BOOKSELLER_DB_PATH`).
- Cannot add a database-level CHECK constraint restricting allowed values for color/material/gender_department (SQLite cannot alter a CHECK constraint without a full table rebuild, and migration 011's comments already establish app-layer-only validation as the pattern for this kind of field).

## Out of scope
- Alias/synonym support (e.g. mapping "TNF" to "The North Face", or "Grey" to "Gray" as two display forms of one canonical value) — COLLATE NOCASE only collapses casing, not synonyms, same as the existing brand feature.
- Any change to the `brand` or `size_label`/`size_system` fields, `clothing_brands`' existing resolve/validate/combobox code paths, or the `size` combobox/system picker.
- Any change to book-category fields (author, publisher) — these remain inherently open-ended free text with no canonical vocabulary.
- Any change to `condition` — it remains a closed CHECK-constraint enum via `ConditionSelect`, not a candidate for this vocabulary pattern.
- Cross-tenant vocabulary sharing or a global/shared starter vocabulary table — each tenant's seeded rows are independent, insertable, and editable rows, not references to a shared list.
- An admin UI for editing, merging, or deleting canonical vocabulary entries once created — this feature only adds create-via-resolve and read-via-list.
- Analytics or reporting on vocabulary usage/frequency across tenants.
- Backfilling or re-normalizing `color`/`material`/`gender_department` values already stored on existing `clothing_details` rows — seeding only affects the vocabulary tables, not historical item data.

## Acceptance criteria
1. Running the new migration against a fresh scratch database creates `clothing_colors`, `clothing_materials`, and `clothing_departments` tables, each with the specified columns and the `UNIQUE(tenant_id, canonical_name COLLATE NOCASE)` constraint.
2. After migration, querying `clothing_colors`/`clothing_materials`/`clothing_departments` for any existing tenant returns exactly the specified 14/14/5 seeded canonical values (no extras, no omissions, no duplicates).
3. After migration, querying `clothing_brands` for any existing tenant returns exactly the specified 25 seeded canonical brand values in addition to any brands already resolved from prior item submissions.
4. Re-running the migration against an already-migrated database does not error and does not duplicate any seeded row (verified by row count before/after equals row count, or by a `UNIQUE` constraint violation never being thrown).
5. Creating a new tenant after the migration has run and immediately querying its color/material/department/brand vocabulary tables returns the same starter seed set as pre-existing tenants.
6. Calling `resolveCanonicalColor(tenantId, "  gray ")` when tenant already has a "Gray" row returns `"Gray"` (existing casing preserved, no new row inserted); calling it with a value not present in the vocabulary inserts a new row and returns the trimmed value.
7. Two concurrent calls to `resolveCanonicalMaterial`/`resolveCanonicalDepartment`/`resolveCanonicalColor` with the same new (not-yet-seeded) value for one tenant result in exactly one row being inserted; both calls return the same canonical_name with no unhandled exception.
8. `validateColorInput(undefined)` and `validateColorInput("")` do not mark the field invalid (color/material remain optional); `validateColorInput("x".repeat(256))` is rejected as invalid; equivalent behavior holds for `validateMaterialInput` and `validateDepartmentInput`.
9. `GET /api/colors`, `GET /api/materials`, `GET /api/departments` each return 401/redirect-equivalent for an unauthenticated request (matching `requireTenant` behavior on `/api/brands`), and return only the requesting tenant's rows, ordered case-insensitively, capped at 200.
10. Submitting the clothing intake form with a color/material/gender_department value that doesn't yet exist for the tenant creates a new canonical row and stores that item's `color`/`material`/`gender_department` using the resolved canonical value.
11. Submitting the clothing intake form with a color value differing only in case from an existing canonical row (e.g. "GRAY" vs seeded "Gray") stores the item using the existing canonical casing, and does not create a duplicate row.
12. In the rendered `AddClothingForm`, the color, material, and department fields each render as a searchable combobox (role="combobox", ARIA listbox) rather than a plain text input with `<datalist>`.
13. Typing a substring in the color/material/department combobox filters the canonical list case-insensitively and, when there is no exact case-insensitive match, shows an "Add \"{typed}\" as a new {field}" option as the last list item.
14. Keyboard interaction (ArrowDown/ArrowUp to highlight, Enter to select, Escape to close) works identically across `VocabCombobox` instances for color, material, and department, matching `BrandCombobox`'s existing keyboard contract.
15. Existing Playwright E2E tests that `.fill()` the color/material/department inputs directly continue to pass unmodified against the new combobox markup.
16. `brand`, `size_label`/`size_system`, `condition`, and book-category (author/publisher) fields and their backing code are unchanged by this feature (verified by diff scope / no unrelated test regressions in `AddBookForm`, `SizeSystemPicker`, `ConditionSelect`, or brand-specific tests).
17. New/changed lib helpers, API routes, and the `VocabCombobox` component meet the project's enforced coverage thresholds (85/80/85/85) with no regression in overall repo coverage.
